{
  "texts": [
    "The hypothesis of extended cognition (HEC) holds that physical processes external to the brains, and sometimes external to the bodies, of individual cognitive agents are sometimes constitutive of those individuals' cognition (for useful overviews, see Gallagher, 2018; Adams & Aizawa, 2019).",
    "Generally -but not exclusively (see Facchin & Leonetti, 2024) -focusing on human cognitive agency, the contemporary debate about HEC in the philosophy of cognitive science bears comparison with longer running discussions in analytic philosophy of action, or 'action theory', between Davidsonian and Anscombean views of the metaphysics of human intentional agency (see, e.g., essays collected in Aguilar & Buckareff, 2010; Ford et al., 2011).",
    "In part, these are debates about the degree to which a salient psychological phenomenon (here, intentional agency) constitutively depends on how things are in the environment beyond the individual that the phenomenon is attributed to.",
    "It is hard to resist the thought that the two debates have an important bearing on each other -especially when we consider that much of the empirical support adduced in favour of HEC comes from research into a kind of intentional action, sometimes called 'cognitive offloading' (Risko & Gilbert, 2016), that is presented as the means by which cognition comes to be constituted by bodily and environmental processes.",
    "This paper will develop this thought."
  ]
}